      <h1>MIPI vs GMSL vs FPD-Link: Which Interface Is Best?</h1>

      <p>When designing a vision system for robotics or automotive applications, one of the first architectural decisions is the camera interface. The three most common options — MIPI CSI-2, GMSL, and FPD-Link III — each have different trade-offs in bandwidth, cable length, complexity, and cost.</p>

      <h2>At a Glance</h2>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>MIPI CSI-2</th><th>GMSL2/3</th><th>FPD-Link III</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Max Data Rate</strong></td><td>2.5 Gbps/lane</td><td>6-12 Gbps</td><td>6 Gbps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Max Cable Length</strong></td><td>~500mm</td><td>10-15m</td><td>10-15m</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Cable Type</strong></td><td>FFC / Flexible</td><td>Coaxial / STP</td><td>Coaxial / STP</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Latency</strong></td><td>Very low</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Connector</strong></td><td>Board-to-board</td><td>FAKRA / H-MTD</td><td>FAKRA / H-MTD</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Complexity</strong></td><td>Simple</td><td>Medium</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Cost</strong></td><td>Lowest</td><td>Medium-High</td><td>Medium-High</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Power over Cable</strong></td><td>No</td><td>Yes (PoC)</td><td>Yes (PoC)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>MIPI CSI-2: Best for Short-Distance, Embedded Vision</h2>
      <p><strong>MIPI</strong> (Mobile Industry Processor Interface) was designed for connecting cameras to processors within a single device — think phone cameras, laptop webcams, and Raspberry Pi cameras.</p>

      <h3>Strengths</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Simplest implementation: sensor connects directly to SoC</li>
        <li>No additional serializer/deserializer chips needed</li>
        <li>Lowest cost and lowest power consumption</li>
        <li>Widely supported by all major SoCs (NVIDIA Jetson, Qualcomm, NXP i.MX, Rockchip)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Weaknesses</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Very short cable length (practically limited to ~300-500mm)</li>
        <li>Sensitive to EMI without proper shielding</li>
        <li>No power delivery over the cable</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Best for</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Robot navigation cameras mounted close to the compute unit</li>
        <li>Prototype and development boards</li>
        <li>Compact embedded vision modules</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>GMSL: Best for Automotive and Long-Distance Vision</h2>
      <p><strong>GMSL</strong> (Gigabit Multimedia Serial Link) by Maxim/Analog Devices is the dominant serdes interface in automotive camera systems.</p>

      <h3>Strengths</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Long cable runs (10-15m over coaxial cable)</li>
        <li>High bandwidth (up to 12 Gbps with GMSL3)</li>
        <li>Power over Cable (PoC) — sensor powered through the same cable</li>
        <li>Excellent EMI immunity with coaxial cable</li>
        <li>Supports bidirectional control channel</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Weaknesses</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Requires serializer and deserializer ICs on both ends</li>
        <li>Higher cost (ICs + coaxial cable + FAKRA connectors)</li>
        <li>Component availability can be constrained</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Best for</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Automotive surround-view and ADAS cameras</li>
        <li>Robot arms with cameras at the end-effector</li>
        <li>AGVs/AMRs with cameras far from the compute unit</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>FPD-Link III: The Alternative to GMSL</h2>
      <p><strong>FPD-Link III</strong> by TI (Texas Instruments) is GMSL's primary competitor. It offers similar performance with a different ecosystem.</p>

      <h3>Best for</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Same applications as GMSL</li>
        <li>Projects where TI components are preferred or more available</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Decision Framework</h2>
      <pre><code>Is your camera within 500mm of the SoC?
├── YES → Use MIPI CSI-2 (simplest, cheapest)
└── NO → Do you need power over the cable?
    ├── YES → Use GMSL or FPD-Link III
    └── NO → Still consider GMSL/FPD-Link for signal integrity over distance</code></pre>

      <h2>Practical Recommendations</h2>

      <h3>For robot startups and makers</h3>
      <p>Start with <strong>MIPI CSI-2</strong>. It is the path of least resistance, and most development kits (Jetson, Raspberry Pi) support it natively. If cable length becomes an issue, migrate to GMSL later.</p>

      <h3>For automotive projects</h3>
      <p><strong>GMSL or FPD-Link III</strong> is mandatory. The automotive environment requires long cable runs, EMI immunity, and power over cable — none of which MIPI provides.</p>

      <h3>For industrial automation</h3>
      <p>Depends on the application. If the camera is close to the controller, MIPI works. If cables need to run along a robot arm or through a machine, use GMSL or FPD-Link.</p>

